Ergo, Mr. Beckett was never
really in jeopardy.

29:54.270 --> 29:55.910
That trial,
for all intents and purposes,

29:55.910 --> 29:59.180
never happened.

29:59.180 --> 30:01.540
- Very clever, Mr. stone.

30:01.550 --> 30:03.180
- I hope there's a "but" coming.

30:03.180 --> 30:04.410
- Sorry, counsel.

30:04.420 --> 30:08.780
But the trial of Mr. Beckett
for arson and felony murder

30:08.790 --> 30:11.290
of Paul Marcus will proceed.

30:11.290 --> 30:13.520
- Thank you, your honor.

30:13.530 --> 30:15.860
It's getting crowded
in that cage.

30:21.530 --> 30:23.570
- From the burn patterns,
we determined

30:23.570 --> 30:26.540
that the fire originated
in a back room of the warehouse,

30:26.540 --> 30:29.440
with the help of an accelerant.
- Which was?

30:29.440 --> 30:31.410
- Gasoline.

30:31.410 --> 30:33.880
Based upon construction of
the warehouse and the fire load,

30:33.880 --> 30:36.480
we determined that the fire was
burning for at least 30 minutes

30:36.480 --> 30:38.710
when Mr. Beckett called 911.

30:38.720 --> 30:40.680
- Did you find that odd?
- Yes.

30:40.690 --> 30:42.620
His residence
was on the property,

30:42.620 --> 30:44.890
less than 100 yards
from the warehouse.

30:44.890 --> 30:46.760
Dozens of pigs burned to death.

30:46.760 --> 30:49.390
There's no way someone
in the house couldn't smell it.

30:49.390 --> 30:52.500
- Hm.
Tell us about Paul Marcus.

30:52.500 --> 30:54.460
- He was an employee
of Mr. Beckett.

30:54.470 --> 30:57.600
Apparently, he was asleep in the
warehouse when the fire started.

30:57.600 --> 30:59.840
He died from smoke inhalation.

30:59.840 --> 31:01.570
No further questions.

31:06.410 --> 31:08.840
- In the first trial,
you testified

31:08.850 --> 31:10.710
that it was possible

31:10.720 --> 31:13.720
this fire was caused
by an electrical short.

31:13.720 --> 31:16.590
Didn't you?
- I said it was possible,

31:16.590 --> 31:18.520
but we found gas dispersion
in places

31:18.520 --> 31:20.460
where gas wasn't supposed to be.

31:20.460 --> 31:22.790
- But it was possible.
- When I said that,

31:22.790 --> 31:26.630
I meant that...
- yes or no?

31:26.630 --> 31:29.600
- Sure.
- Thank you.

31:29.600 --> 31:31.430
- When we initially
questioned Mr. Beckett,

31:31.440 --> 31:33.640
I smelled gasoline
on his person.

31:33.640 --> 31:37.840
- He said he spilled the gas
while he was filling up his car.

31:37.840 --> 31:39.510
So we checked
the surveillance cameras

31:39.510 --> 31:42.510
at the gas station
he said he went to that day

31:42.510 --> 31:44.510
and neither he nor his car
were ever there.

31:44.520 --> 31:48.680
- After the fire marshal
told us he suspected arson,

31:48.690 --> 31:50.520
we checked
Mr. Beckett's financials

31:50.520 --> 31:52.820
and we learned that he was
in financial trouble.

31:52.820 --> 31:54.820
- Could you please
be more specific?

31:54.830 --> 31:56.690
- He owed nearly $2 million.

31:56.690 --> 31:58.260
Finally, we learned
that his property

31:58.260 --> 31:59.800
was insured for $3 million.

31:59.800 --> 32:01.630
That's when we arrested him.

32:01.630 --> 32:07.570
- Thank you.

32:07.570 --> 32:10.440
- How many gas stations
were there within ten miles

32:10.440 --> 32:13.280
of Mr. Beckett's property?

32:13.280 --> 32:14.280
- Three or four.

32:14.280 --> 32:15.850
- There were five, actually.

32:15.850 --> 32:17.710
Did you check
the surveillance cameras

32:17.720 --> 32:19.880
at the other four gas stations
close by?

32:19.880 --> 32:22.590
- No. We checked the one
he said he used.

32:22.590 --> 32:26.490
- Mr. Beckett's property
just burned down.

32:26.490 --> 32:30.830
His business... everything he
owned... got destroyed.

32:30.830 --> 32:32.730
Now is it possible
that he made a mistake

32:32.730 --> 32:36.600
when he told you
what gas station he used?

32:36.600 --> 32:38.000
- Yeah, I guess.

32:38.000 --> 32:40.640
- In your experience,
is it rare for a business

32:40.640 --> 32:43.770
to insure itself against fire?

32:43.780 --> 32:46.810
- No.
- Thank you.

32:48.580 --> 32:51.850
- Paul and I were married
for 13 years.

32:51.850 --> 32:54.080
He loved working with pigs.

32:54.090 --> 32:55.950
Ever since summers
in high school.

32:55.950 --> 33:00.760
I never understood it,
but Mr. Beckett paid him okay.

33:00.760 --> 33:02.760
- How long did he work
for Mr. Beckett?

33:02.760 --> 33:04.530
- Since he opened the farm.

33:04.530 --> 33:07.630
Maybe three years.

33:07.630 --> 33:10.870
- I know this is difficult,
Mrs. Marcus,

33:10.870 --> 33:15.770
but please tell us
about the night Paul died.

33:15.770 --> 33:18.670
- We had a fight...
Like all married people...

33:18.680 --> 33:20.740
About something stupid.

33:20.750 --> 33:22.910
- Do you remember
what you fought about?

33:22.910 --> 33:26.550
- He went bowling after work
with his friend Mel,

33:26.550 --> 33:30.120
and we were supposed to
have dinner at my mom's.

33:30.120 --> 33:34.890
That he wasn't going to
sleep in my bed that night.

33:34.890 --> 33:37.090
He grabbed a six pack
and he left.

33:37.100 --> 33:41.530
He was huffy like that.

33:41.530 --> 33:45.530
He slept in Mr. Beckett's barn.
He had a key.

33:45.540 --> 33:47.940
The next morning,
there was a cop at my door

33:47.940 --> 33:52.040
telling me that my husband
had died in a fire.

33:54.380 --> 33:56.880
- I'm sorry.

33:56.880 --> 34:00.580
- I don't even know
where our son is.

34:00.590 --> 34:03.990
He just left because
he blamed me for his dad dying.

34:03.990 --> 34:06.390
And now...

34:06.390 --> 34:07.990
I'm just alone.

34:14.800 --> 34:19.570
Three lives ruined, Mr. Beckett.
Was it worth it?

34:19.570 --> 34:21.100
- Objection.
- No further questions.

34:21.110 --> 34:22.840
- I have no questions.

34:27.909 --> 34:31.679
- All I ever wanted was
a business of my own, you know?

34:31.679 --> 34:35.120
- Was there a problem?
- Not at first.

34:35.120 --> 34:37.590
I took out a loan
to lease some land

34:37.590 --> 34:41.120
and build a small farm and
warehouse to package fresh meat.

34:41.130 --> 34:43.190
Within a couple of months,
the county was up my ass

34:43.190 --> 34:46.199
about fixing a pot hole
in the driveway.

34:46.199 --> 34:49.600
And there was a fine
attached to that, of course.

34:49.600 --> 34:51.600
Then the fda shows up.

34:51.600 --> 34:54.139
They say that my packing
was mislabeled

34:54.139 --> 34:57.840
because even though
my chickens are cage-free,

34:57.840 --> 35:00.140
they're not cage-free
according to the government.

35:00.140 --> 35:04.210
Why? Because there's
an irrigation pipe 25 feet below

35:04.220 --> 35:06.450
and an opening in the dirt.

35:06.450 --> 35:08.120
And that was another fine.

35:08.120 --> 35:12.720
Then there was the epa
for cow flatulation.

35:12.720 --> 35:17.060
They say that the design
of my livestock waste lagoon

35:17.060 --> 35:18.230
was a half an inch shallow.

35:18.230 --> 35:20.060
They said I would have
to build a whole

35:20.060 --> 35:23.700
brand new indoor facility.
- Did you?

35:23.700 --> 35:26.740
- It would've cost
over a million dollars.

35:26.740 --> 35:30.170
The fine's got to be
$20,000 per day.

35:30.170 --> 35:31.970
Who can afford that?

35:31.980 --> 35:34.680
I owed over $2 million.

35:34.680 --> 35:36.780
Maybe I got a little sloppy
or careless

35:36.780 --> 35:39.650
with the electric
in the warehouse.

35:39.650 --> 35:43.220
- What did you do with the
insurance money you received?

35:43.220 --> 35:46.120
- I paid off
the damn government.

35:49.190 --> 35:54.030
I am sorry about
what happened to Paul.

35:54.030 --> 35:56.800
And I feel for Gail.

35:56.800 --> 35:58.270
But there is just no way in hell

35:58.270 --> 36:00.000
I'd burn down my own farm.

36:06.510 --> 36:08.980
- I feel for you, Mr. Beckett.

36:08.980 --> 36:13.020
Perhaps you consoled yourself
on your 41-foot yacht.

36:15.250 --> 36:18.120
- Okay, that was stupid.
I admit it.

36:18.120 --> 36:21.190
But I was working hard,
I thought I'd treat myself.

36:21.190 --> 36:23.830
- To a $500,000 boat.

36:23.830 --> 36:26.900
- I had a loan.
It's the American way, right?

36:26.900 --> 36:29.230
- So you also used
your insurance money

36:29.230 --> 36:31.070
to pay off your boat loan.

36:31.070 --> 36:32.200
- And what's wrong with that?

36:32.200 --> 36:33.840
- Nothing.

36:33.840 --> 36:35.770
Until you sold
the $1/2 million boat

36:35.770 --> 36:39.110
to a juror to fix
your arson case.

36:39.110 --> 36:41.240
- I didn't know what to do.

36:41.250 --> 36:43.910
I didn't do anything wrong
and the next thing I know,

36:43.920 --> 36:46.280
I'm on trial for murder.

36:46.280 --> 36:48.950
You know, all of you...
The cops, the firemen,

36:48.950 --> 36:51.120
the whole damn government,
and you, Mr. stone...

36:51.120 --> 36:54.260
You can't let a decent man run
his business and live his life.

36:54.260 --> 36:56.330
- A decent man wouldn't
kill an employee in a fire

36:56.330 --> 36:59.230
he started for money.
- Is there a question?

36:59.230 --> 37:02.060
- Ask the cop.
Yeah, maybe he smelled gasoline.

37:02.070 --> 37:05.170
But you ask him about the burns
on my clothes and my hands.

37:05.170 --> 37:08.240
- Are you saying
you tried to save Paul Marcus?

37:08.240 --> 37:11.170
- I already said I didn't know
he was in the warehouse.

37:11.180 --> 37:13.280
I tried to save the pigs.

37:13.280 --> 37:16.880
The fire was everywhere and
I was trying to get them out.

37:16.880 --> 37:19.150
But they were out of
their minds, screaming.

37:19.150 --> 37:21.250
Have you ever heard
a pig scream?

37:21.250 --> 37:25.020
You can't just open a gate and
let them run out like horses.

37:25.020 --> 37:27.160
You gotta grab 'em
by the back legs.

37:27.160 --> 37:28.860
And they're 200 pounds.

37:35.300 --> 37:38.800
- Mr. stone?

37:38.800 --> 37:40.600
Sorry, judge.

37:40.610 --> 37:43.270
Uh...

37:43.270 --> 37:48.280
You grab the pigs by the...

37:48.280 --> 37:50.250
Grab the pigs by the back legs
and then what?

37:50.250 --> 37:53.220
- Do you know what it takes
to wrangle a pig?

37:53.220 --> 37:55.880
You gotta put your knee
in their back and grab an ear

37:55.890 --> 37:59.320
and then maybe... maybe
they'll do what you want.

37:59.320 --> 38:01.220
- Nothing further.

38:04.030 --> 38:07.300
- That's it for today.

38:07.300 --> 38:10.200
- You wanna talk? Hm?

38:10.200 --> 38:12.030
- I'll listen.

38:18.170 --> 38:20.980
- Why is she here?
- I invited her.

38:20.980 --> 38:22.180
If you're uncomfortable,
we can wait to hear

38:22.180 --> 38:24.980
what the jury decides.
- No, that's fine.

38:24.980 --> 38:27.250
Okay, the way I see it,
we pretty much

38:27.250 --> 38:29.850
fought this to a draw.
- I see it differently.

38:29.850 --> 38:32.220
- All you've got
is bribing a juror.

38:32.220 --> 38:35.220
Was pretty convincing.
- You know what?

38:35.230 --> 38:38.030
I'll roll the dice.
I'll take my chances.

38:38.030 --> 38:39.290
- That's fine with me.

38:39.300 --> 38:43.100
We'll worry about
the other charges later.

38:43.100 --> 38:44.830
- What's he talking about?

38:44.840 --> 38:46.300
- Murdering Ted Cody.

38:46.300 --> 38:49.070
- The knife was excluded.
You have no evidence.

38:49.070 --> 38:51.110
- Well, maybe,
but I've got a narrative.

38:51.110 --> 38:56.680
Cody was blackmailing
your client for bribing a juror.

38:56.680 --> 38:58.280
He decided he didn't want
to pay anymore.

38:58.280 --> 39:00.120
- You can't prove anything.

39:00.120 --> 39:04.120
What you're looking at are
pictures of Ted Cody's injuries.

39:04.120 --> 39:06.220
There's the bruised ankles
and the broad bruising

39:06.220 --> 39:08.990
on his back and neck,
which was, of course, broken.

39:08.990 --> 39:10.930
Let's not forget
the torn earlobe.

39:12.230 --> 39:16.030
You wrangled Ted Cody
just like you wrangled pigs.

39:16.030 --> 39:19.000
Add to that the free meat,
the cash in Cody's freezer,

39:19.000 --> 39:21.000
Ms. caufield's testimony,
and the fact that

39:21.010 --> 39:22.270
you're pretty much
a low-life in general,

39:22.270 --> 39:25.240
and I've got one hell
of a story for the jury.

39:25.240 --> 39:28.340
Oh, and I'll make sure that
your sentences run consecutively

39:28.350 --> 39:32.210
so you'll be out
when you're 130.

39:32.220 --> 39:35.220
- Last meat on the bone, huh?
That's what you want.

39:35.220 --> 39:36.950
- I could be happy
with you in stateville

39:36.950 --> 39:40.320
for the next 35 years.

39:40.320 --> 39:42.290
Which is a bargain,
considering the minimum

39:42.290 --> 39:45.130
for two murders is natural life.

39:55.310 --> 39:59.040
- Yeah, right. Okay.

39:59.040 --> 40:00.310
What the hell?

40:00.310 --> 40:02.240
- I wanna hear you say
you killed Ted Cody.

40:02.250 --> 40:05.450
- He was a dirty cop.
- Clock's ticking.

40:09.020 --> 40:11.320
No deal.

40:11.320 --> 40:15.160
- Yeah, okay.

40:15.160 --> 40:17.260
Sure.

40:17.260 --> 40:19.060
I killed him.

40:21.500 --> 40:23.530
- And Paul Marcus.

40:32.080 --> 40:33.210
- I killed Paul Marcus.

40:40.350 --> 40:42.320
Shame on you!

41:07.040 --> 41:09.380
- All I can say is I'm glad
I don't eat meat.

41:09.380 --> 41:11.010
- Guess it's true what they say.

41:11.020 --> 41:12.480
Never ask how
the sausage is made.

41:15.820 --> 41:18.350
- For a minute,
I felt for Beckett.

41:18.360 --> 41:21.820
I mean, all those regulations,
he was suffocating.

41:21.830 --> 41:26.260
- We get the government
we deserve, Anna.

41:26.260 --> 41:28.330
- It's for you from Gail Marcus.

41:40.010 --> 41:44.310
What's that?

41:44.320 --> 41:47.350
It's the reason I do what I do.

41:47.350 --> 41:49.220
- Drink up while you can, folks.

41:49.220 --> 41:51.290
'Cause starting tomorrow,
I'm shut down for four days

41:51.290 --> 41:54.360
to fix some problem that
the health inspector found.

42:04.030 --> 42:06.640
- Got 'im.
- Yeah, we did.
